The goal of this page is to build up knowledge from a somewhat undergraduate
level, and arrive at the concepts needed to understand and intuite the math
surrounding some of the more complex cryptographic concepts.

# Glossary

## [Field]($section.id('field'))

A **field** is a [set](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)) where
can you add, subtract, multiply, and divide (except by zero), and all of the 
usual algebraic rules work.

Example:
- Ration numbers [`\mathbb{Q}`](/$)
- Real numbers [`\mathbb{R}`](/$)
- Finite fields such as [`\mathbb{F}_5 = \{0, 1, 2, 3, 4\}`](/$), with 
addition and multipliction done `mod 5`.

When we say "finite field" we mean there are finitely many elements.
For every prime number `p`, there's a finite field with exactly `p` elements,
written [`\mathbb{F}_p`](/$).

---

## [Group]($section.id('group'))

A **group** is a simpler algebraic structure - you only have one operation
(like multiplication), and:

1. You can combine any two elements.
2. The operation is associative.
3. There's an identity element. An element where `x op identity = x`.
4. Every element has an inverse.

For example, the nonzero elements of [`\mathbb{F}_p`](/$), 
written [`\mathbb{F}_p^*`](/$), form a multiplicative group under modular multiplication.

[`\mathbb{F}_5^* = \{1, 2, 3, 4\}`](/$) is a cyclic group of order 4.

---

## [Cyclic Group]($section.id('cyclic_group'))

A [group](#group) is **cyclic** if there exists one element `g` (called a generator) such
that every element of the group can be written as a power of `g`.

In [`\mathbb{F}_5^*`](/$), for example, `g = 2` works as the generator because,

```=mathtex
\begin{align*}
2^1 \bmod 5 \equiv 2 \\
2^2 \bmod 5 \equiv 4 \\
2^3 \bmod 5 \equiv 3 \\
2^4 \bmod 5 \equiv 1
\end{align*}
```

All elements in [`\{1, 2, 3, 4\}`](/$) can be expressed as a power of 2, mod 5.
So the group is *cyclc*.

---

## [Order of an Element]($section.id('order'))

The **order** of an element [`x`](/$) in a [group](#group) is the 
smallest positive integer [`m`](/$) such that [`x^m = 1`](/$).

For instance, in [`\mathbb{F}_5^*`](/$), the order of 2 is 4, since [`2^4 \equiv 1 \bmod 5`](/$).

---

## [Roots of Unity]($section.id('roots_of_unity'))

Elements whose power equal `1` are called *roots of unity*.

The *m-th roots of unity* are all elements [`x`](/$) such that [`x^m = 1`](/$).

In [`\mathbb{F}_5^*`](/$), the 4-th roots of unity are `{1, 2, 3, 4}`, since each
satisfies [`x^4 = 1 \bmod 5`](/$).

---

## [Subgroup]($section.id('subgroup'))

A **subgroup** is a smaller [group](#group) that lives inside of a larger
group and follows the same rules.

Formally, if [`(\mathbb{G}, \cdot)`](/$) is a group (under multiplication),
a subset [`\mathbb{H} \subseteq \mathbb{G}`](/$) is a subgroup if:

1. The operation of [`\mathbb{G}`](/$) keeps you inside [`\mathbb{H}`](/$)
    - For all [`a, b \in \mathbb{H}`](/$), [`a \text{ op } b \in \mathbb{H}`](/$).
2. The identity of [`\mathbb{G}`](/$) is in [`\mathbb{H}`](/$).
3. Every element of [`\mathbb{H}`](/$) has an inverse, which is also in [`\mathbb{H}`](/$).

For example let's look at [`\mathbb{F}_7^* = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}`](/$). This group
has order 6.

We can see that `3` is a generator of this group,

```=mathtex
\begin{align*}
3^1 \bmod 7 \equiv 3 \\
3^2 \bmod 7 \equiv 2 \\
3^3 \bmod 7 \equiv 6 \\
3^4 \bmod 7 \equiv 4 \\
3^5 \bmod 7 \equiv 5 \\
3^6 \bmod 7 \equiv 1
\end{align*}
```

So [`\langle3\rangle = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}`](/$). This means 3 is a generator
of the whole group [`\mathbb{F}_7^*`](/$), making it a [cyclic group](#cyclic_group).

We can look at a *subset* of this group, when we use 6 instead of 3.

```=mathtex
\begin{align*}
6^1 \bmod 7 \equiv 6 \\
6^2 \bmod 7 \equiv 1 \\
6^3 \bmod 7 \equiv 6 \\
...
\end{align*}
```

When raising 6 to higher and higher powers, it will *cycle* between
6 and 1. This subset, [`\{1, 6\}`](/$), satisfies all subgroup rules:

- `1` is the identity.
- It is closed under multiplication.
- Inverses exist, [`6^{-1} = 6`](/$).

Interestingly, the order of the subgroup (2 in this case) always divides the order
of the whole group. This shows off 
[Lagrange's theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_theorem_(group_theory)), 
which states:

> The order of a subgroup divides the order of the whole group.

---

## [Finite Field Extensions]($section.id('finite_field_extensions'))

Finite fields are fields with a finite number of elements. Every finite field
has an order (size) [`q`](/$).

We can generalize finite field extensions by starting not from a prime field 
[`\mathbb{F}_p`](/$), but from any finite field [`\mathbb{F}_q`](/$) of
order [`q = p^n`](/$), where [`p`](/$) is a prime, and [`n`](/$) is a positive
integer.

To construction a larger field [`\mathbb{F}_{q^n}`](/$), we adjoin a new element 
[`x`](/$) that satisfies an irreducible polynomial of degree [`n`](/$) over 
[`\mathbb{F}_q`](/$).

Formally,
```=mathtex
\mathbb{F}_{q^n} = \mathbb{F}_q[x] / (f(x))
```
where [`f(x)`](/$) is irreducible over [`\mathbb{F}_q`](/$).

Every element of [`\mathbb{F}_{q^n}`](/$) can be written as a polynomial of
degree less than [`n`](/$) with coefficients in [`\mathbb{F}_q`](/$):

```=mathtex
a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 + \dots + a_{n-1}x^{n-1}, \quad a_i \in \mathbb{F}_q
```

This way, [`\mathbb{F}_{q^n}`](/$) is an *n*-dimensional vector space over
[`\mathbb{F}_q`](/$).

## [Field Towers]($section.id('field_towers'))

Field extensions can themselves be used as bases for further extensions.
This leads us to the idea of **field towers**.

Let's start with a base field [`\mathbb{F}_p`](/$), given some prime [`p`](/$),
and we'll build up to [`\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}}`](/$).

By setting [`q = p`](/$) and [`n = 2`](/$), we can extend the base field to 
[`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$):

```=mathtex
\mathbb{F}_{p^2} = \mathbb{F}_p[u] / (u^2 + 1)
```

Here [`u`](/$) is a root of the irreducible polynomial [`f(u) = u^2 + 1`](/$) 
over [`\mathbb{F}_p`](/$). In this field, multiplication is done modulo
[`u^2 + 1 = 0`](/$), so we have the following relation:

```=mathtex
u^2 \equiv -1 \pmod{p}
```

Each element of [`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$) can be written as:

```=mathtex
a + b u, \quad a, b \in \mathbb{F}_p
```

This only works if [`-1 \pmod{p}`](/$) is a quadratic residue, but for our
example we can just assume it is. How to determine whether it is and what
it implies on other aspects of elliptic-curve cryptography is a bit outside
of the scope of this post.

Now to extend [`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$) by degree 3 to get [`\mathbb{F}_{p^6}`](/$).
We define:

```=mathtex
\mathbb{F}_{p^6} = \mathbb{F}_{p^2}[v] / (v^3 - \xi)
```

Here [`\xi`](/$) is a quadratic non-residue in [`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$) - that is,
there's no element [`x \in \mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$) such that [`x^2 = \xi`](/$).
This ensures that [`v^3 - \xi`](/$) is irreducible.

Similar to the 2nd degree extension, arithemtic is performed modulo [`v^3 = \xi`](/$),
giving the relation:

```=mathtex
v^3 \equiv \xi \pmod{u^2 + 1}
```

Each element of [`\mathbb{F}_{p^6}`](/$) can be written as:

```=mathtex
(a_0 + a_1 v + a_2 v^2), \quad a_i \in \mathbb{F}_{p^2}
```

And finally we land at the final extension, by degree 2, to get [`\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}}`](/$).
The math looks nearly the same as our first quadratic extension:

```=mathtex
\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}} = \mathbb{F}_{p^6}[w] / (w^2 - v)
```

Here [`w`](/$) satifies [`w^2 = v`](/$), and since [`v`](/$) was a cubic
non-residue in [`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$), this final extension is also irreducible.

So we have the defining residue:

```=mathtex
w^2 \equiv v \pmod{v^3 - \xi}
```

And each element of [`\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}}`](/$) can be expressed as:

```=mathtex
(b_0 + b_1 w), \quad b_i \in \mathbb{F}_{p^6}
```

At each layer, the arithmetic re-uses the lower-level operations. For example,
multiplication in [`\mathbb{F}_{p^{12}}`](/$) can be implemented using three
multiplications in [`\mathbb{F}_{p^6}`](/$), which in turn reduce to operations
in [`\mathbb{F}_{p^2}`](/$).

---


